               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270405-259-person1451">
                  WILLIAM 
                  HOWARD TURNER
               <interp inst="t18270405-259-person1451" type="surname" value="HOWARD TURNER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270405-259-person1451" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270405-259-person1451" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am brother to George Turner and Charlotte Turner; they are in partnership, as <rs id="t18270405-259-viclabel1418" type="occupation">pump and engine manufacturers</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270405-259-victim1449 t18270405-259-viclabel1418"></join>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270405-259-victim1450 t18270405-259-viclabel1418"></join> - the prisoner was quite a stranger - I know nothing of this matter.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270405-259-person1452">
                  WILLIAM 
                  COLTON
               <interp inst="t18270405-259-person1452" type="surname" value="COLTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270405-259-person1452" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270405-259-person1452" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable. On the 25th of February I saw the prisoner, and another young man, with him, near Red Lion-street, Holborn, about seven o'clock in the evening; it was quite dark; I followed him nearly a mile to Mr. Turner's factory, near the Temple, in Whitefriars; I saw the prisoner get over a high iron railing, and<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182704050107"></xptr>hand something over, but I could not see what it was, as it was dark; I know there was a great quantity of iron pipes for pumps, deposited there; they then went up a court by the side of the glass-house, which led them round to Water-lane. I followed them, but lost sight of them in a court; I then met them again in Shoe-lane (I had taken sufficient notice of them to know they were the same persons); when they got to the end of Shoe-lane the other one gave it again to the prisoner; I then took the prisoner, and asked him where he got it; he said a man gave it him to carry; his companion got away; I could not hold them both; I found it was this piece of iron-pipe - I took it down to Messrs. Turner's, and there we found a broken pipe - this piece exactly matched it.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Q. Was it not possible that when I got over the rails you could take me? A. Yes.</p>
               <p>MR. TURNER. I saw this pipe brought back, and have no doubt whatever that it was a part of the stock there - it is worth about 1s. 6d.; the yard is surrounded by a high wall.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. At the time he took it from under my arm, I looked round and told him that was the man who gave it me; he would not take him, but took me, and said, "Why did not you tell me what you had got, and I would have let you go?" he asked the night-constable if he was willing to let me go; he said "No," as the charge was given.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18270405-259-verdict1419" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18270405-259-verdict1419" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 19.</p>
